WELLINGTON, Dec 19 (Reuters) - Following are some of the lead stories from New Zealand metropolitan newspapers on Friday.

Stories may be taken from either the paper or Internet editions of the papers. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.  DOMINION POST(www.stuff.co.nz) Lochinver deal worth $88 million: Aspiring Lochinver Station buyer Shanghai Pengxin does now not expect to hear if the Government will consent to the NZ$88 million deal until February at the earliest. - - - - Farmers working hard to reduce emissions intensity: The emissions intensity of New Zealand agriculture, that is the gases generated per unit of meat or milk produced on farms, has declined on average by about 1 per cent since at least 1990. - - - - FMA warning over UK pension 'press-gang': The Financial Markets Authority has issued a warning over potentially misleading advertising about transferring British pension scheme funds to New Zealand. - - - -   NEW ZEALAND HERALD (www.nzherald.co.nz) Carter rings in a so-so start for Arvida: As Grant Adamson lay in hospital after a brain aneurism Michael Ambrose gave the late retirement village visionary a promise - one that was kept with the float of Arvida Group <ARV.NZ>. - - - - Telcos bury hatchet for cable: Vodafone <VOD.L> and Spark <SPK.NZ> chiefs Russell Stanners and Simon Moutter have put aside competition to partner up and build the transtasman telecommunications cable along with Telstra <TLS.AX>. - - - - Finzsoft plans takeover bid: The managing director of Finzsoft Solutions <FIN.NZ>, Andrew Holliday, says he will make a discounted takeover bid for the financial software developer in partnership with Bermuda IT company Silverlake Axis. - - - -